title: Neutron induced pion production on C,Al,Cu and W at 200-600 MeV

x4freetext: Experiment performed at WNR area of
LAMPF. 800 MeV proton beam from linear accelerator
was sent to tungsten target from which a continuous
energy neutron beam was produced by spallation
reaction.The beam line was located at 30deg relative
to the proton beam. Macropulses of width up to 500
mus was delivered to target at a repetition rate of
20-60Hz. Micropulses had a width of 0.25 ns and a
variable spacing greater than 1 mu-s.
Six multiwire delay line chambers
were used to track particles through the magnetic
spectrometer to allow measurement of scattering
angle and momentum of particles. Scintillation
detectors were used for particle identification,
form measurement of neutron energy by time of
flight and to give start signal for delay lines of
drift chambers.
Fission chamber was used to monitor the
neutron flux
Several samples with natural isotopic composition
and thickness of 0.3 - 1.2 mg/cm2 were used.
Total uncertainty consiting of
statistical uncertainty
systematic uncertainty in neutron
flux determination
systematic uncertainty in cross
section calculation
Compiled by S.H.
